ival. For television, Bridges directed several works by David Mercer and Dennis Potter.\nPeter Bradshaw on theguardian.com film blog wrote: \"Bridges was a brilliant poet and cinematic satirist – in tones both mordant and melancholy – of the English class system of the early 20th century, and a director with a flair for psychology and interior crisis, as evidenced by movies like The Return of the Soldier (1982) and The Shooting Party (1985).\"\n\n", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2022-05-19T10:42:48.402065+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 1576, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alan_Bridges"}], "uuid": "1127f8d2-66e4-4dea-b0aa-1dd1541cfdf5", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "14736", "external_references": [{"id": 6903, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q920584"}, {"id": 6904, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "72873247"}, {"id": 6905, "source": {"name": "LOC Auth", "slug": "loc-auth"}, "source_identifier": "n86075277"}, {"id": 6906, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "lccn-n86075277"}], "date_modified": "2023-09-13T12:28:02.352307+10:00"}]}